Events.RelatedBody:
We have two ASP NET Core websites running in a Linux environment which communicate using HTTP requests.

On one server we are manually creating the new HTTP request and adding a provided cookie collection to the request like so:

`CookieCollection cookies` is passed to the method

```
// Create the request
var request = WebRequest.CreateHttp(OtherServerUrl);
request.Method = "POST";
request.ContentType = "application/json;charset=UTF-8";

// Add cookies if we have specified.
if (cookies != null)
{
    // Create new cookie container if one does not exist.
    if (request.CookieContainer == null)
    request.CookieContainer = new CookieContainer();

    // Add our cookies to the container.
    request.CookieContainer.Add(cookies);
}

if (content != null)
{
    // Serialize the model
    var JSONBody = JsonConvert.SerializeObject(content);

    // Write the json into the request stream
    using (var requestStream = await request.GetRequestStreamAsync())
    using (var sw = new StreamWriter(requestStream))
        await sw.WriteAsync(JSONBody);
}

// Get the request response as a HttpWebResponse
var response = (await request.GetResponseAsync()) as HttpWebResponse;
.....
```

In our use case, currently only a single cookie is being added, but we can see this if we output the request's cookie container; the cookie is in the request before it is sent. But when the request reaches the endpoint on the other server, the cookie container in the request contains 0 cookies.

The exact same code runs fine on Windows with the cookies being passed correctly, it only appears to occur on Linux.

In asp.net, based on [Tracing in ASP.NET Web API 2](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/web-api/overview/testing-and-debugging/tracing-in-aspnet-web-api), there is ITraceWriter interface and you could do something like below to enable tracing for infra logic.

```C#
public static void Register(HttpConfiguration config)
{
    config.Services.Replace(typeof(ITraceWriter), new SimpleTracer());
}
```

I don't see this Api exists anymore for asp.net core, and I tried to search on internet but also does not see anyone mention a replacement solution.

In the past, we leveraged this in our production service to trace the execution flow to help trouble-shooting latency issue, what is the replacement for it in asp.net core 2.1?

### Roles are cached for too long
So, I wanted to create an admin-only panel. That's all fine and dandy, and the mechanism ended up working. However, ASP.NET Core caches the role for too long (at first I thought it was my code), and if I add or remove the role, I have to either log out and then log back in or wait around ~10 minutes (don't quote me on that) for the admin-only panel to appear/disappear. It's very annoying.

### Functional impact
If an admin gets demoted for abusing their powers, they will still have admin powers on the website until the cached role resets.

### Minimal repro steps
1. I'm using the current code:
```
@page
@model App.Pages.Account.Manage.AdminPanelModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "AdminPanel";
    var isAdmin = User.IsInRole("Admin");
}

@if (isAdmin)
{
    <h2>Hello, fellow administrator.</h2>
     //WIP
}
else
{
    Response.StatusCode = (int)Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.StatusCodes.Status401Unauthorized;
    <h2>You are not authorized.</h2>
}
``` 
and creating the Admin role in Startup using RoleManager.
2. Try adding/removing the role to/from the user.
If it's added to the user, the admin panel should pop up immediately.
If it's removed from the user, the admin panel should disappear.

### Expected result
Changes should be effective almost immediately.

### Actual result
Changes take a lot of time to go into effect.
